        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>HPE secures $1B AI deal with Musk’s X:</strong> Hewlett Packard Enterprise has secured a <a href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-13-01-2025-m1-6-1-billion-deal" target="_blank">$1 billion deal</a> to supply AI-optimized servers to Elon Musk’s X platform. Competitors Dell and Super Micro also made a bid but lost out. AI hardware demand surges as companies like Tesla and xAI adopt cutting-edge technologies. HPE shares rose 1% following the news, signaling strong investor confidence in its AI-driven growth strategy. The report also added that the agreement was reached late last year.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Enbridge plans pipeline expansion under Trump:</strong> Enbridge is preparing to increase US <a href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-13-01-2025-m2-7-oil-pipeline-capacity" target="_blank">oil pipeline capacity</a> as the Trump administration aims to boost drilling. The company’s CEO highlighted plans to move more oil from the Rockies and Bakken regions to Gulf Coast refineries. Enbridge’s move aligns with US energy dominance goals. However, potential tariffs on Canadian oil could complicate cross-border projects like Line 5.</p>
