        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Biden’s rule curbs cooking oil imports:</strong> The US Treasury has ruled out <a href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-13-01-2025-m3-8-tax-credit-for-biofuels" target="_blank">tax credits for biofuels</a> made from foreign-used cooking oil to benefit US soybean farmers. The decision boosted soybean oil futures by 7% and lifted shares of biofuel giants like Darling Ingredients by 10%. The move is part of Biden’s Inflation Reduction Act. It aims to strengthen domestic renewable diesel production while countering concerns over fraudulent UCO imports from Asia.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Uranium prices soar amid AI energy demand:</strong> Uranium prices have hit a record <a href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-13-01-2025-m4-9-190-per-separative-work-unit" target="_blank">$190 per separative work unit</a>. The surge is driven by the demand for AI data centers. The industry also faces a supply crunch due to sanctions on Russian uranium and limited conversion capacity in the West. Big Tech companies like Microsoft are turning to nuclear power for energy-intensive operations, adding pressure to an already strained market.</p>
        </mj-text>
