              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What are the Basel Accords?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-13-3.jpg" alt="What are the Basel Accords?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The Basel Accords are international banking rules created by the Basel Committee to make the global financial system safer. These rules help banks manage risks better and ensure they have enough money (capital) to handle losses during tough economic times. By doing this, the Basel Accords aim to prevent financial crises and keep the banking sector stable.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">There are three key Basel Accords. <strong>Basel I (1988)</strong> set the first rule that banks must hold at least 8% of their risky assets as capital. <strong>Basel II (2004)</strong> added rules for managing other risks, like market and operational risks, and required banks to be more transparent about their finances. <strong>Basel III (2010)</strong> was introduced after the 2008 financial crisis to make banks even stronger. It included stricter rules on how much money banks need to keep, new rules to ensure banks can handle cash flow issues, and limits on risky activities.</p>
        </mj-text>
